VALUES (
    'Style Manifesto: How to Build a Capsule Around Statement Footwear',
    'Editorial advice for assembling a seasonal wardrobe anchored by hero shoes, complete with rituals, palettes, and care systems.',
    '<h2>Step 1 &mdash; Identify Your Hero Pair</h2>
     <h3>Hero Audit</h3>
     <p>Pick one pair per category (sleek loafer, bold runner, rugged boot). Each becomes the focal point around which everything else orbits. Lay pairs on kraft paper, photograph overhead, and annotate feelings: <strong>confidence</strong>, \"boardroom armor,\" \"sunset sprint.\" The audit includes heel height, toe shape, and silhouette notes. Strike-through duplicates you rarely wear; underline pairs that spark compliments. Heroes earn their status by narrative and utility, not hype alone.</p>
     <h3>Story Mapping</h3>
     <p>For each hero, write a mini origin story: where it was made, what materials whisper, why you reached for it during pivotal moments. Embed italic quotes from artisans if available. This story informs outfit choices later—velvet loafers referencing jazz clubs beg for satin trousers and smokey eyes. Mapping stories ensures your capsule feels cinematic rather than chaotic.</p>
     <h3>Gap Analysis</h3>
     <p>Overlay your hero list with lifestyle demands. Do you have a pair for monsoon commutes? Desert weddings? Underground raves? Highlight gaps in neon. This prevents impulse buys and keeps the capsule purposeful. <u>Wishlist items</u> derived from gaps carry more meaning than random scrolly cravings.</p>
     <h2>Step 2 &mdash; Color Mapping &amp; Palette Orchestration</h2>
     <h3>Neutral Foundation</h3>
     <p>Draft two palettes: everyday neutrals and accent tones. Start with base shades (bone, charcoal, olive) that ground looks. Swatch them beside your heroes to confirm compatibility. Use footwear gradients to bridge both—ombre laces, dip-dyed soles, painted edges. <strong>Palette boards</strong> live on your wall, triggering creativity every morning.</p>
     <h3>Accent Play</h3>
     <p>Choose accent tones that echo personal mythology—maybe cobalt from your hometown flag or persimmon from grandma’s sari. Limit to three to avoid chaos. Apply accents through socks, scarves, or lash lines. Capture combos in a notes app, adding strikethrough when fatigue hits so you cycle fresh mixes.</p>
     <h3>Seasonal Modulation</h3>
     <p>Rotate palettes quarterly. Spring invites dusty pastels, summer loves saturated brights, autumn leans into rust, winter demands metallic sparks. Track reactions from friends or clients; their compliments become datapoints guiding future tweaks. <em>Color mapping</em> is part science, part poetry.</p>
     <h2>Step 3 &mdash; Texture Stacking &amp; Material Dialogue</h2>
     <h3>Contrast Recipes</h3>
     <p>Pair patent leather with brushed knits, contrast matte nubuck against satin cargos, layer technical mesh with structured outerwear. Create texture recipes on index cards, noting weather suitability and care needs. Sensory language matters—\"feels like hugging thunder\" gets you dressed faster than \"black jacket.\"</p>
     <h3>Sensory Wardrobe Walkthroughs</h3>
     <p>Once a month, touch every piece in your closet. Close eyes, run fingers along seams, listen to rustles. This ritual deepens connection and reminds you of maintenance tasks. Highlight friction points (boots rubbing hems) and adjust hemlines or add guards. <u>Texture stacking</u> thrives when clothes love each other.</p>
     <h3>Accessories as Amplifiers</h3>
     <p>Belts, bags, and jewelry echo hero textures. A rugged boot loves hammered metal cuffs; a silk-wrapped mule sings with pearl anklets. Document accessory pairings so packing becomes plug-and-play. Keep a \"Styling Lab\" shelf where experiments wait for the right day.</p>
     <h2>Step 4 &mdash; Outfit Formulas &amp; Documentation</h2>
     <h3>Template Creation</h3>
     <p>Create templates (work, weekend, after hours). Document them in your notes app for quick reference. Each template includes hero shoe, top, bottom, layer, accessory, and mood. Use bulletproof naming (\"Gallery Opening\" vs \"Look 4\"). <strong>Formula grids</strong> reduce decision fatigue.</p>
     <h3>Lookbook Building</h3>
     <p>Shoot looks with timers or friends, cataloging angles and lighting. Tag photos with keywords (\"rainy,\" \"pitch,\" \"dancefloor\"). Sync to cloud folders accessible on travel. Strikethrough combos that no longer align; style evolves.</p>
     <h3>Scenario Drills</h3>
     <p>Run scenario drills like fire drills. \"Client called, dinner in two hours.\" \"Flight delayed, need comfy yet polished.\" Dress, time yourself, adjust formulas. This playfulness reveals gaps (need packable blazer?). Document improved formulas for future crunches.</p>
     <h2>Step 5 &mdash; Maintenance Rituals &amp; Tracking</h2>
     <h3>Rotation Dashboard</h3>
     <p>Rotate shoe trees, log wears, refresh laces monthly, and run quarterly deep cleans. Build a spreadsheet tracking mileage, compliments, repairs. Conditional formatting turns cells gold when a pair deserves a spa day. <strong>Maintenance dashboards</strong> treat care like celebration, not chore.</p>
     <h3>Care Kits and Scheduling</h3>
     <p>Stock care kits by shoe type: suede brushes, leather balm, mesh wipes. Set calendar reminders for cleaning, resoling, or lace swaps. Add italic notes about weatherproofing before trips. Share schedules with cobblers; they appreciate proactive clients.</p>
     <h3>Legacy Planning</h3>
     <p>Decide which heroes you’ll resell, gift, or archive. Label boxes with stories so recipients know why they matter. Photograph wear patterns as art; post them with captions honoring miles traveled. <u>Style legacy</u> extends beyond outfits—it documents a life in motion.</p>
     <p>Download printable checklists and closet planner grids inside the ShoeStore app.</p>',
    3,
